text:
To those blaming the members who speak multiple languages:

There's something that some people who don't speak a second language don't understand. The fact that you understand what people are saying, doesn't mean you can translate easily. For example, my native language is Spanish, but when I speak in English, I am not translating in my head, I AM THINKING in English. I have friends in the US that only speak English, and when I tell them this, they get very confused, like the concept of thinking in a language different than your native one is not possible.

Only immature people will lash out at other content creators for things like this. :-(

author: @THEGRAYGRIFFIN

text:
¬†@thefourthdymensionmusic¬† That's how it is my friend. Learning to speak another language, is learning to think in that language. Imagine having a conversation with a native speaker and you have to translate in your head everything! That just doesn't work.

About learning Spanish, the two main things you need to remember (at least in my opinion) is how to conjugate verbs for different times and people, you will start noticing a pattern on the endings of the words, which will make it easier to know what the correct word is, even if you only know the infinitive verb. The second rhing is simply vocabulary. One thing that you can do (I used to do it when I was first learning English) is to look around your house and see if you know the Spanish word for everything you see. That's a surprisingly easy and not time-consuming way of learning useful day to day vocabulary.
author: @THEGRAYGRIFFIN

text: ¬†@NeinKyori¬† I know! I was able to write and read in English, long before I was able to have fluent conversations

text:
I keep seeing people trying to incite a fan-war in the comment section. Let me try and quell this.

First its not the players fault, its how the game was setup.

The players where mostly beginners, "disabling ejection confirmation, visual task and anonymous voting",  highly favored impostors especially in a game with mostly beginners. Also the chance of learning immediately after mistakenly voting out someone is taken away from them . 

Then add the natural JP and ID players familiarity with each other, since the play on the same minecraft server vs the segregated EN players. Couple that with a language barrier and Amelia being impostor most of the time.

There's little room to listen or trust the EN players and with one of their own casting blame all of the time, hell why even give them a chance. 

This game was a melting pot waiting to happen,  both Gura and Calli were stressed out and its a shame one of them has the highest sub.

text:
¬†¬† Some of Gura's die-hard fans (probably from her old channel and don't actually care about hololive as a whole) were upset and have been aggressive in other vtuber's chats and social media because they felt Gura was being "bullied" because she kept dying/being voted on when in fact she just doesn't play the game well, this game emphasizes trying to stay as a group as much as possible, not going off on your own when you're most vulnerable which is what Gura was doing most of the time. Following others a lot of the time not only protects you from being killed, but also gives you an alibi.

It doesn't help with the language barrier, Gura doesn't explain things well that is easy for the JP vtubers to understand, she needs to use more simple phrases and make more use of the in-game chat and game specific expressions like what Amelia did.
Also I feel like Gura took the game too seriously, it's supposed to be a fun/light-hearted experience with other vtubers but it felt like she was treating it like a competition and her negative reactions affect how those die-hard fans feel about things. She needs to keep in mind where she is and who she's playing with, don't stress over a game that you're playing in a collab otherwise you risk your fans attacking the other vtubers. All collabs should be for fun, not competitive nature, majority of viewers are watching because they like the vtubers, not the gameplay.

Gura really needs to address her fans on these issues otherwise the toxic behaviour will continue.

Something else to note: Many of the JP vtubers make an effort to learn simple English phrases before playing these games (they all know what things like "sus" means and the English names for areas of the map etc), the English vtubers should make an effort to do the same in return.

text:
‚Äã¬†@KingMufasa_8¬† Hear me out here. 
Its not the players fault, its whoever set the collab up, the manager.

Most of the players being beginners. Then disabling ejection confirmation and visual task and anonymous voting, is a recipe for stress. (These are not settings for casuals players)


Then add the natural JP and ID players biases for not playing with EN regularly,  7:3 ratio (JP & ID game on the same minecraft server making them more familiar with each other, while EN is segregated), and language barrier. 

The risk of someone tilting massively in this game was high. Just sad it had to be the one with most subs and the biggest voice.

text:
Jealous of what? Her great stress? She isn't Fubuki or Korone who streams for years and has big experience. Yes, it's unfair, sure, but c'mon, many of Hololive (and Holostars) members speaks japanese-only and they got themselves some good numbers when they started to just try speaking english. Seriously, many new english subscriers coming to unpopular Moona, Iofi and Risu right now (how much people knew about Hololive-ID actually speaking fine english?), Fubuki and Korone got their 1 million faster because of Hololive fanzone growth, and et cetera. But what about our shark? What about our tsundereaper? What about Ame-mama? What about Bottom Left? One who almost completely fine (*doubts*) is taco, though she's taking it easy with her content, but the others?

Gura? Do you remember her awful (in more than one meaning) streams? Maneater stream? "Time to enchant" stream? This stream? Yeah, it sure is better when 700k people see your failures and pain. Let's watch Pekora's first videos, there are only 50k or even less views. It's not even a comparison with Gura's first videos.
Calli? Oh, yes, sudden popularity sure is great when you have potato PC and actually noob in games? Not to mention those damn red superchats.
Amelia? Yes, sure is great to have a massive community of backseaters, lewders, toxic-spammers and perverts of all fetishes from start. 
Kiara? Not to mention potato PC again, but her progress in comparison? Lowest subs count in Hololive EN despite of all the hype?  Not so great popularity with japanese viewers, though her japanese is the best of all EN girls and she always tries to translate herself?

Actually, some "senpais" (not by subs count, of course) seeking for collaboration with english branch, because they're actually on hype right now. But do they really "jealous"? Lol, not at all, I think.

I don't think it was just "gura not being more convincing", instead everyone not putting more thoughts into the game

text:
The funny thing is about 25% of what made Gura suffer is that she's actually pretty good at the detective aspect of the game - and in general she's more well-reasoned (if clumsy) than people realize - but that makes you look more suspicious through a language barrier. It's actually just a big problem with discourse that people who tend toward engaging in good faith end up being singled out, but especially through a language barrier when you try to reason things out carefully it just makes you more difficult to understand and thus exaggerates the "she's talking too much" problem, despite innocent people having just as much reason to talk or be nervous.

The other problems are 25% that she was sleep deprived (she was extra out of it here) and 50% that she got plain unlucky with the draw on all the early deaths.

text:
Having heard about the salt all day and finally watched the full stream, the salt was justified. I can summarize it like this: 
Gura: suspects correct person 
Imposter: "no u"
And Gura gets voted out (big oof) 

Feel free to skip the stuff below, just my two cents that no one asked for :)
on the real, the voting discussions were definitely harder to follow than the last collab. Language barrier is of course a factor, but I don't think it's only that since the last collab went so smoothly. I feel when two generations collab as opposed to a lot of random members, they already have solid intrageneration chemistry so there isn't as much awkwardness (which helps with the language barrier). On that note, I'd love to see a collab with HoloFantasy since they have such good chemistry (plus Marine has been really active on the EN streams)

text:
¬†@deepmoist¬† nah, I just like to analyze Among Us streams in objective way. Gura did get some disadvantages here, but she clearly did many bad moves herself. She's definitely a better player in the lobby but only slightly, while most others are total beginners who don't even know some of the rules. And the frustating part from Gura's play is not only the discussion but also the exploration part. Gura was killed by impostor 5 times, and 4 of them were because she wandered alone, not because they're targeting her. In a beginner lobby like this, the only safe kill for beginners' imposter is targetting nearby lone crewmates. And I think that's her biggest mistake here. If she sticks with 1-2 other people, her survival chance would be bigger.

Other girls definitely performed even worse by throwing left and right, but as the better player I get why Gura gets frustated. I just really disappointed that many shrimps lashes out on the other girls as bullying Gura, and let alone while not acknowledging her mistakes.

text:
*Edited for clarity and because people seem to think I have something against HoloJPN for not being able to speak English lol
As someone who speaks Japanese and who has worked as a Japanese TA in college, and who has also taught English to Japanese students- I think it's odd that they're even doing collabs with groups this large without a proper translator in the first place. I totally get them wanting to bridge the gap between the two groups and their audiences (and members like Kiara, Coco, and even Haachama , Cali, and even Ina exemplify this). That's how we get beautiful relationships like Pekora x Moona. But they created Hololive-EN for a reason- to cater to the English speaking audience. If they wanted the two groups to collab this much they should've made basic conversational Japanese a requirement for entry. I think it's kinda unfair for the Holo-EN members to feel pressured to learn a completely new language when their group was made to cater to a different audience. The same can be said for the HoloJPN members and English. Otherwise BOTH the non-English/Japanese speaking members will always end up falling back on and deffering to the members that have a better grasp of the other language which ultimately leads to frustrating, hard to watch situations like Gura's this stream. Moona was in the same boat early on as well during the ID x JPN collabs. 
What happened in this stream isn't the fault of any of the members bullying Gura or HoloEn. It's a result of Hololive management thinking that throwing the girls together to play games without a proper mediator will just magically work out somehow. Kiara is extroverted and confident enough to usually do that but this time she's not here, Cali isn't proficient enough to do that and Lofi was just super passive this time around. This stream is a result of that corporate mindset.
If more and more streams like this keep happening, HOPEFULLY that'll spur the Hololive staff and memners to at least TRY and improve both their Japanese/English skills.

author: @noobadhi7029

text:
‚Äã¬†@yubangaw¬† That's the exact point I'm making. Let me say this again: I think it's a wonderful thing for the two branches to be reaching out to each other like this and doing their best to collaborate and forge friendships through the language barrier. That's great. That's how we end up with beautiful relationships like Pekora x Moona.
That being said, if Yagoo/Hololive as a company had the intention of having these crossover streams since the concept of Holo EN was created, I don't understand why they didn't at least make it a requirement for the members to have basic Japanese conversation skills. Otherwise BOTH the non-English/Japanese speaking members will always end up falling back on and deffering to the members that have a better grasp of the other language which ultimately leads to frustrating, hard to watch situations like Gura's this stream. Moona was in the same boat early on as well during the ID x JPN collabs. 
I say this as someone who worked as a Japanese TA during college and as someone who's taught English to Japanese students.

The Holo JPN members I can understand because (assuming they all graduated High School) they should've all learned the basics of English at the very least (whether or not they've retained that knowledge is up in the air), but they can at least hold passable, broken conversations. Conversely, Japanese isn't a mandatory subject in any English speaking country that I know of so the native English speakers are already on the back foot.
If more and more streams like this keep happening, HOPEFULLY that'll spur the Hololive staff to advise all members to at least TRY and improve both their Japanese/English skills.

text:
Biggest problem I see is that there's no one that could control the conversations. On the Amon9 Us collab, they had Kiara and Botan combo to handle the talks.

We could argue that from the others' perspective, it's all fun and chaos, enjoyable even. But I'd say it's not a sustainable condition if they're planning for more future collabs like this. So some tweaks might be necessary.

I also want to clarify that it's not that the "translators" are not doing their job. Live translating is already a difficult task, but controlling a conversation is a whole separate beast of itself. It's like saying "You can talk normally to me, so why can't you do public speaking?"

I added quotation marks on "translators" because they are not translators by title. They merely took the role openly so the collab is possible. Which is something that we should already be very grateful of, and unfortunately many have failed to see

text:
This stream...
2 hours of dying first, getting accused, and very bad decisions on all sides.
That... that really stinks, Gura. And the rotten cherry on top was when you got yourself voted out.

I hope you rewatch this last bit, Gura. It'll help you see what actually happened when you thought you saw Risu with the body.
What actually happened was that you got to O2, and your report button showed up. I can only assume that you didn't see it.
About 7 seconds later, Risu came in, and neither of you saw the body for a good 5 seconds afterward until Risu reported it.
I think in your frustrated state, you couldn't see any of that, and simply saw Risu on the body before she reported it.

I feel I should apologize for my comments at the end... seeing you insist so strongly on something that didn't happen was equally frustrating to watch.

All I can offer is my condolences for this round. Some days... some days, life beats you down. Make sure to do the same to it next time.

text: Ah, yes. A Way Out: Sequel. Just kidding. Hey, I know there's been some questionable messages in chat saying that Gura's taking it too seriously but isn't that part of the game? I hope people won't be so quick to judge when she rages. We all have different ways of handling frustrating moments. If I was in her position there, desk-kun wouldn't even survive until the end of stream. Let's keep this lighthearted and wait for Gura's revenge.

text:
¬†@kitsunetenma7951¬† While i agree that nobody is at fault for language barrier stuff, I fail to see how Gura was being "blatantly antagonistic" when she was 1st or 2nd dead for most of the games. She was falsely accused for faking medscan and defended herself, and she was a little salty towards watson in the last game. Voting early =/= playing bad necessarily. 

That being said the real problem was everyone's inexperience with the game. No meetings called EVER, no imposter double kill on 6 left. WAY too much skip voting, and worse than that way too much of no voting at all. Also to be fair you are kinda supposed to be antagonistic to a degree, throwing sus out is a big part of the game whether you are crewmate or imposter
author: @BeatYourAssInHalo

text:
¬†@BeatYourAssInHalo¬†  She defended herself from medscan by starting a large argument. By escalating, she put more sus on herself. Something Ame took advantage of as impostor by killing the one she argued with and saying ‚ÄúGura sus? You guys were arguing...‚Äù That is bad play.

Voting early is not bad play. Voting without discussing what you‚Äôre voting and why til after IS bad play. It heavily implies to others that you‚Äôre eager to get the voting done, the one weapon crewmates have against impostor. Very sus, and very bad play.

Her saltiness was part of the reason for her antagonistic behavior. She almost never calmed down after the first round enough to realize that she was speaking too complex english for almost half of the people there to understand. Amelia got around this by using simple phrases like ‚ÄúI am at [location]‚Äù and ‚Äú[name] sus‚Äù. Gura gave full on sentences like ‚ÄúSuisei is suspicious because she walked right past the body without reporting!!!‚Äù That is bad play, especially when you know your teammates aren‚Äôt good at english.

Also, being salty about dying early kind of made her gameplay deteriorate more. She went in bad places solo and died more often as a result.

Again, she is inexperienced. They all are. None of this is disparaging Gura as a person, but nonetheless, she did not play well, so she died often. Amelia suffered from the same handicaps, played well. Also, I think they had visual tasks off, so falsely accused isnt exactly correct. It was just inexperience in that she didnt realize people couldnt see her do medscan and the others didnt realize that visual tasks were off and that she was not faking.
author: @kitsunetenma7951

text: ¬†@kitsunetenma7951¬† It's good to see someone who can view this in the most calming and logical way without making any of the girls look bad. Truly a person who can help clear things up. I agree, there were lots of moment where Gura made too many complicated gesture and bad decisions making up to the point she got the short end of the straw but it is as you said, many of the girls are inexperienced. They don't know how to properly set themselves up in the game yet. I'm sure over time when they play more together this can be avoided and the gameplay experience would be more engaging and less... Saltiness add to it.
author: @vincenpaul1691

text:
¬†@kitsunetenma7951¬† This is true. Arguments can be unavoidable sometimes, but definitely make you look sus.

Killing someone you argue with can go both ways because as imposter you wanna leave people who are sus alive, and holding grudges/ killing someone you argue with is a bad play. You can use the "why would i kill someone when it makes me look most suspicious if they die" excuse either way. Whether or not it works pretty much depends on if you are trusted enough or not that round. It can be a soft clear in some cases.

For the Suisei part in particular, Nene vouches for her even though they weren't really together at all. Watson says she was with Suisei in lower engine, which Gura immediately knows isn't true and throws more sus, I don't think this part of the convo is quite understood by the JP side. Watson sorta plays it off but still kinda sus. Obviously the Imposters aren't going to vote for themselves here, so Gura needs to convince Calli and Nene. In the end neither of them vote and its a wasted round. Especially on 5 if you don't at least try to vote someone out its an easy win with 2 Imposters left. Calli was trying to translate the last little bit i think, which is why she doesn't vote.  

I really do agree it all boils down to inexperience. Gura was alone too often, but at the same time if everyone groups together it can get really hard for imposter to win. I think there is a delicate balance for everyone to enjoy themselves. I'm not too sure what the other settings were at but it does seem that visual tasks were off, which may not be the best for a group of beginners. Kill cooldown also might have been too long? It seemed like the kills happened pretty slow in some rounds. It'd be nice if they went over the settings at the beginning so everyone is on the same page but i can see how it would be a hassle in two different languages.

Of course i don't mean to be attacking anyone either just sharing my viewpoint. Oh, and they were talking over each other quite a bit, which also makes it harder to understand even if you are fluent in both languages, hopefully they can try to work on that if/when they do more collabs in the future.
